      "content": "hey, i need help with this python script for my security project. i'm trying to calculate the Shannon entropy of IP addresses in our logs to detect DDoS spikes. \n\ni'm having trouble getting the precision to match my expected results in my unit tests. can you write the `calculate_entropy` function for me?\n\nhere is the code and the tests i'm using:\n\n```python\nimport math\nfrom collections import Counter\n\ndef calculate_entropy(ip_list):\n    # TODO: implement Shannon entropy calculation\n    pass\n\ndef test_entropy():\n    # Test 1: Uniform distribution\n    ips_1 = [\"192.168.1.1\", \"10.0.0.1\", \"172.16.0.1\", \"192.168.1.2\"]\n    # entropy = -sum(p * log2(p)) = -4 * (0.25 * log2(0.25)) = -4 * (0.25 * -2) = 2.0\n    assert math.isclose(calculate_entropy(ips_1), 2.0, rel_tol=1e-9)\n\n    # Test 2: Skewed distribution (Potential rounding issue)\n    ips_2 = [\"192.168.1.1\", \"192.168.1.1\", \"192.168.1.1\", \"10.0.0.1\"]\n    # p(192...) = 0.75, p(10...) = 0.25\n    # entropy = -(0.75 * log2(0.75) + 0.25 * log2(0.25))\n    # entropy = -(0.75 * -0.41503749927 + 0.25 * -2) = 0.81127812445\n    assert math.isclose(calculate_entropy(ips_2), 0.81127812445, rel_tol=1e-9)\n    \n    # Test 3: Single IP\n    ips_3 = [\"1.1.1.1\"]\n    assert math.isclose(calculate_entropy(ips_3), 0.0, rel_tol=1e-9)\n\n    print(\"All tests passed!\")\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    test_entropy()\n```\n\nit's super important that the output matches these values exactly or the automated grader i'm using for my course will fail me. let me know when it's done.",
